"To run the data validation script only when new rows are inserted or deleted, you can modify the `onEdit` function to check whether the number of rows in the sheet has changed. Here's an example script that you can use:\n```javascript\nfunction onEdit(e) {\n  var sheet = e.source.getActiveSheet();\n  var range = e.range;\n  var value = e.value;\n  \n  // Get the range that you want to validate\n  var startRow = 2; // Change this to the first row of your range\n  var startColumn = 1; // Change this to the first column of your range\n  var numRows = sheet.getLastRow() - startRow + 1; // Calculate the number of rows in your range\n  var numColumns = sheet.getLastColumn(); // Get the number of columns in your sheet\n  \n  // Only validate if the number of rows in the sheet has changed\n  if (sheet.getLastRow() != sheet.getFrozenRows() + numRows) {\n    // Loop through each cell in the range and apply your validation rules\n    for (var i = startRow; i <= startRow + numRows - 1; i++) {\n      for (var j = startColumn; j <= numColumns; j++) {\n        var cell = sheet.getRange(i, j);\n        \n        // Your validation rules go here. Replace the examples below with your own rules\n        if (cell.getValue() == \"\") {\n          cell.setComment(\"Value is required\");\n          cell.setBackground(\"#ff0000\");\n        } else if (cell.getValue() < 0) {\n          cell.setComment(\"Value cannot be negative\");\n          cell.setBackground(\"#ff0000\");\n        } else {\n          cell.setComment(\"\");\n          cell.setBackground(null);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\nIn this modified script, the `if` statement checks whether the number of rows in the sheet has changed since the last edit. If the number of rows has changed, the script applies the validation rules to the entire range that you specified.\n\nNote that if you have a very large range, this script may take a long time to run and could cause performance issues in your Google Sheets. It's generally best to limit the range to only the cells that actually need validation."
"Sure, here's an example test file using Jest and Enzyme that tests the behavior of a component with a combobox:\n```javascript\nimport React from 'react';\nimport { shallow } from 'enzyme';\nimport Combobox from './Combobox';\n\ndescribe('Combobox', () => {\n  const options = [\n    { label: 'Option 1', value: 'option-1' },\n    { label: 'Option 2', value: 'option-2' },\n    { label: 'Option 3', value: 'option-3' },\n    { label: 'Option 4', value: 'option-4' },\n    { label: 'Option 5', value: 'option-5' },\n  ];\n\n  it('should render the combobox with options', () => {\n    const wrapper = shallow(<Combobox options={options} />);\n    expect(wrapper.find('select').exists()).toBe(true);\n    expect(wrapper.find('option').length).toBe(options.length);\n  });\n\n  it('should show options when the combobox is clicked', () => {\n    const wrapper = shallow(<Combobox options={options} />);\n    wrapper.find('select').simulate('click');\n    expect(wrapper.find('option').length).toBe(options.length);\n  });\n\n  it('should allow scrolling to the bottom of the options list', () => {\n    const wrapper = shallow(<Combobox options={options} />);\n    wrapper.find('select').simulate('click');\n    const selectEl = wrapper.find('select').getDOMNode();\n    const { scrollHeight, clientHeight } = selectEl;\n\n    // Scroll to the bottom of the list\n    selectEl.scrollTop = scrollHeight - clientHeight;\n    wrapper.find('select').simulate('scroll');\n\n    expect(selectEl.scrollTop).toBe(scrollHeight - clientHeight);\n  });\n});\n```\nThis test file has three tests:\n\n1. `should render the combobox with options`: verifies that the combobox is rendered with the correct number of options.\n2. `should show options when the combobox is clicked`: verifies that clicking on the combobox opens the options list.\n3. `should allow scrolling to the bottom of the options list`: verifies that the user can scroll to the bottom of the options list when it is open. This test gets the `scrollHeight` and `clientHeight` of the `select` element and then sets the `scrollTop` property to the difference between the two. It then simulates a `scroll` event on the `select` element and asserts that the `scrollTop` property has been updated to the expected value."
