"Sure, here's an example function to plot the counts of each unique value in the \"unit\" column:\n```scss\ndef plot_unit_counts(self):\n    counts = self.df['unit'].value_counts()\n    plt.bar(counts.index, counts.values)\n    plt.xticks(rotation=90)\n    plt.title('Count of Requests by Unit')\n    plt.xlabel('Unit')\n    plt.ylabel('Count')\n    plt.show()\n```\nTo add it to the class object, we can simply define the function within the class definition:\n```ruby\nclass AHDParser:\n    def __init__(self, file_path):\n        self.df = pd.read_csv(file_path, encoding='ISO-8859-1')\n        ...\n\n    def save_to_csv(self, file_path):\n        self.df.to_csv(file_path, index=False)\n\n    def plot_unit_counts(self):\n        counts = self.df['unit'].value_counts()\n        plt.bar(counts.index, counts.values)\n        plt.xticks(rotation=90)\n        plt.title('Count of Requests by Unit')\n        plt.xlabel('Unit')\n        plt.ylabel('Count')\n        plt.show()\n```\nNow, after creating an instance of the class, we can call `plot_unit_counts()` on it to generate the plot:\n```scss\nahd_parser = AHDParser('smpl_small_df.csv')\nahd_parser.plot_unit_counts()\n```"
