"You can add the following lines to the script to check if the source folder is empty before deleting it:\n```\n$items = Get-ChildItem -Path $source.FullName -Recurse\n\nif($items -eq $null){\n    Remove-Item -Path $source.FullName -Recurse -Force\n}\n```\nThis script uses the `Get-ChildItem` cmdlet to check if there are any items in the source folder. If the variable $items is null, it means that the folder is empty, and the `Remove-Item` cmdlet is used to delete the source folder. The `-Recurse` parameter ensures that any subfolders within the source folder are also deleted, and the `-Force` parameter deletes the folder without prompting for confirmation.\n\nSo your final script would look like\n```\n$source = Get-ChildItem -Path \"C:\\\" -Recurse | Where-Object {$_.PSIsContainer -eq $true -and (Get-ChildItem $_.FullName).Count -gt 1} | Select-Object -First 1\n$destination = \"C:\\destination\\\"\n\nGet-ChildItem -Path $source.FullName -Recurse | Move-Item -Destination $destination\n\n$items = Get-ChildItem -Path $source.FullName -Recurse\n\nif($items -eq $null){\n    Remove-Item -Path $source.FullName -Recurse -Force\n}\n```\nIt will first move all the files and folders, then check if the source folder is empty, if it is empty then it will delete the source folder."
