"If your library is built using CMake, the process for debugging native crashes using LLDB in Android is slightly different. Here are the steps you can follow:\n\n1. Enable Native Debugging: Enable native debugging in your Android Studio project by adding `android:debuggable=\"true\"` to your app's `AndroidManifest.xml` file or adding `debuggable true` to your `build.gradle` file.\n2. Reproduce the Crash: Run your app on your Android device and reproduce the crash. Once the crash occurs, your device will generate a tombstone file. You can find this file in `/data/tombstones/` directory on your device.\n3. Pull the Tombstone File: Pull the tombstone file from your Android device to your development machine using the `adb` command:\n```php\nadb pull /data/tombstones/<tombstone file name> <destination path>\n```\n4. Generate CMake Build Files: Generate CMake build files for your native library by running the following command:\n```bash\ncd <path-to-your-native-library>\nmkdir build && cd build\ncmake .. -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug -DCMAKE_TOOLCHAIN_FILE=<path-to-your-ndk>/build/cmake/android.toolchain.cmake -DANDROID_ABI=<abi> -DANDROID_NATIVE_API_LEVEL=<api-level>\n```\nThis command generates CMake build files for your native library in a new `build` directory.\n5. Build Your Library: Build your native library using the following command:\n```scss\ncmake --build . --target <target> -- -j$(nproc)\n```\nReplace `<target>` with the name of the target you want to build. For example, if your library is named `mylib`, you can build it by running:\n```scss\ncmake --build . --target mylib -- -j$(nproc)\n```\n6. Start LLDB: Navigate to your project's directory and start LLDB by running the following command:\n```vbnet\nlldb -- <path-to-your-shared-library>\n```\nReplace `<path-to-your-shared-library>` with the path to your built native library.\n7. Load the Core File: In the LLDB prompt, load the core file by running the following command:\n```css\ntarget create --core <path-to-the-tombstone-file>\n```\nThis command loads the tombstone file into LLDB.\n8. Analyze the Crash: Now that you have loaded the tombstone file into LLDB, you can analyze the crash. Use LLDB commands such as `thread list`, `thread select`, `frame info`, and `bt` to investigate the crash and find the root cause.\n9. Fix the Issue: Once you have identified the issue, fix it and rebuild your app.\n\nNote: This is a general process for debugging native crashes using LLDB in Android when your library is built using CMake. The specific steps may vary depending on your app and the nature of the crash."
"The error message suggests that Nginx is unable to locate the SSL certificate file for your domain. This can be caused by a few different issues, such as a misconfigured file path or incorrect file permissions.\n\nHere are some steps you can take to troubleshoot this issue:\n\n1. Check the SSL certificate file path: Verify that the file path for the SSL certificate is correct. In the `docker-compose.yml` file, make sure that the `volumes` section for the `nginx` service includes the correct path to the SSL certificate files. For example:\n```javascript\nvolumes:\n  - ./nginx/conf.d:/etc/nginx/conf.d\n  - ./nginx/ssl:/etc/nginx/ssl\n```\nMake sure that the SSL certificate files (`fullchain.pem` and `privkey.pem`) are located in the `nginx/ssl` directory.\n2. Check the file permissions: Verify that the SSL certificate files have the correct file permissions. In the `nginx/ssl` directory, run the following command to set the correct file permissions:\n```bash\nchmod 600 fullchain.pem privkey.pem\n```\n3. Restart the containers: After making any changes, restart the Docker containers by running the following command:\n```\ndocker-compose down\ndocker-compose up -d\n```\nThis will stop and remove the containers, and then start them again with the updated configuration.\n\nOnce you have completed these steps, try accessing your website again to see if the issue has been resolved. If you still see the error message, check the Nginx logs for any new error messages that may have been generated."
