"Sure, here's an example of how you can determine if a user's savings have reached a full Hijri year using Flask and Python:\n```python\nimport hijri_converter\nfrom datetime import datetime\n\ndef calculate_zakat_due(savings_amount, user_id):\n    # Get the current Hijri year\n    current_hijri_year = hijri_converter.Gregorian(datetime.now()).to_hijri().year\n    \n    # Calculate the Hijri year for the savings_amount\n    hijri_year = hijri_converter.Gregorian(datetime.now().replace(month=1, day=1) - timedelta(days=1) + relativedelta(years=-savings_amount))).to_hijri().year\n    \n    # Check if the difference between the current and savings Hijri year is >= 1\n    if current_hijri_year - hijri_year >= 1:\n        # Create a new zakat record in the database\n        zakat_amount = savings_amount * 0.025\n        due_date = datetime.now() + timedelta(days=30)\n        zakat_record = Zakat(user_id=user_id, savings_amount=savings_amount, zakat_amount=zakat_amount, due_date=due_date)\n        db.session.add(zakat_record)\n        db.session.commit()\n\n        # Update the user's current zakat due\n        user = User.query.get(user_id)\n        user.current_zakat_due = zakat_amount\n        user.current_zakat_due_date = due_date\n        db.session.commit()\n```\nHere, we're using the `hijri_converter` library to convert between Gregorian and Hijri dates. We first get the current Hijri year using `datetime.now()` and the `to_hijri()` method. We then calculate the Hijri year for the savings\\_amount by subtracting the number of years equivalent to the savings\\_amount from the current year. We then compare the difference between the current and savings Hijri year to see if it's greater than or equal to 1. If it is, we create a new zakat record in the database and update the user's current zakat due.\n\nNote that this code assumes that you have a `Zakat` model with columns for `user_id`, `savings_amount`, `zakat_amount`, `due_date`, and a `User` model with a `current_zakat_due` and `current_zakat_due_date` column. You'll also need to import the necessary libraries and set up a database connection."
"I apologize for the oversight in my previous response. I see the problem now. If no exceptions occur during the critical section, the lock will not be released. To fix this, we should use `finally` to ensure that the lock release action is always executed, whether an exception occurs or not.\n\nHere's the corrected implementation:\n```haskell\nimport Control.Exception\nimport Control.Concurrent.STM\n\nwithLock lock f = uninterruptibleMask $ \\restore  -> do\n  restore (atomically (takeTMVar lock))\n  (restore f) `finally` atomically (putTMVar lock ())\n```\nIn this implementation, the `finally` function ensures that the lock release action, `atomically (putTMVar lock ())`, is always executed, whether an exception occurs within the critical section or not. The rest of the implementation remains the same as previously discussed.\n\nThis corrected implementation addresses all the concerns we discussed throughout our conversation and ensures that the lock is properly released in all cases, including when no exceptions occur during the critical section."
