"The Zugot were pairs of Jewish leaders who headed the Sanhedrin, the supreme council of ancient Israel, between the periods of the Great Assembly and the rule of King Herod in the late Second Temple period. According to Jewish tradition, there were five pairs of these teachers: (1) Jose b. Joezer and Jose b. Johanan, who flourished at the time of the Maccabean wars of independence; (2) Joshua b. Pera\u1e25yah and Nittai of Arbela, at the time of John Hyrcanus; (3) Judah b. \u1e6cabbai and Simeon b. Shata\u1e25, at the time of Alexander Jannaeus and Salome Alexandra; (4) Shemaiah and Abtalion, at the time of Hyrcanus II; and (5) Hillel and Shammai, who were the last of the zugot and lived during the period of Herod the Great. Other sages who are considered part of the group of the 120 elders include Chaggai, Zechariah, Malachi, Daniel, Chananiah, Mishael, Azariah, Nechemiah ben Chakaliah, Mordechai the linguist, and Zerubavel [[1](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zugot)][[2](https://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/15293-zugot)][[3](https://www.britannica.com/topic/zugot)][[4](https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/zugot)][[5](https://judaism.stackexchange.com/questions/94216/who-were-the-leaders-of-the-jewish-religion-between-ezra-and-the-1st-zugot)]."
