"I want a c++ class that i can use to define the rules to.use when i have to kill processes when something happens during a testing run.\n\nWhen instantiated, the only object of this class will get a list of executables paths in the specified directory. Absolute paths are memorized.\n\nThe user of the class can call a function to specify the rules to be observed when killing of the processes has to happen. The user specifies the name of an executable or of a list of executables and specifies the rules to be observed by giving a list of flags (from an enum).\n\nWhen killing processes, the class enumerates the running processes and for each process name that is known, it must determine if the process is to be killed or not.\n\nThe rules to be specified by the user of the class are:\n1. If a process is enumerated and known, should it be killed or not and should we kill it only if its path is in the given directory or wherever it's path is\n2. Should we kill the descendants of this process or not\n3. If the process is a descendant of a known process and is known, should it be killed or not and should we kill it only if its path is in the given directory or wherever it's path is\n4. If the process is a descendant of a known process and is not known, should it be killed\n\nA function can be called by the user when the killing of the process has to happen and the rules are used to determine which processes must be killed (we list the pids of processes to kill).\nAfter the list of pids to kill has been made, all the processes in the list are killed by calling TerminateProcess if the process is still alive at this time. If the process is already dead, we just skip it. If we try to kill a process and we have an error, we verify again if it's alive and we issue an error only if it's still alive. Errors are listed and we report a list of error in the end."
