"To show that the binary relation \u227f is a preference relation, we need to prove that it is complete and transitive.\n\n1. Completeness:\nFor any two alternatives x and y in the set X, either x \u227f y or y \u227f x (or both) must hold true. Since the utility function u represents the binary relation \u227f, we can use it to compare the alternatives.\n\nFor any two alternatives x and y, we can calculate their utility values u(x) and u(y). Since u(x) and u(y) are real numbers, either u(x) \u2265 u(y) or u(y) \u2265 u(x) (or both) must hold true. This directly implies that either x \u227f y or y \u227f x (or both), which satisfies the condition for completeness.\n\n1. Transitivity:\nFor any three alternatives x, y, and z in the set X, if x \u227f y and y \u227f z, then x \u227f z must hold true. Again, we can use the utility function u to compare the alternatives.\n\nSuppose x \u227f y and y \u227f z. This implies that u(x) \u2265 u(y) and u(y) \u2265 u(z). Since the utility values are real numbers, we can use the properties of real numbers to deduce that u(x) \u2265 u(z). This directly implies that x \u227f z, which satisfies the condition for transitivity.\n\nSince we have shown that the binary relation \u227f is both complete and transitive, we can conclude that \u227f is a preference relation."
