"Yes, you'll need to upload the `data.json` file to AWS Lambda so that it can be accessed by your function.\n\nOne way to do this is to include the `data.json` file in your deployment package when you create your Lambda function. You can do this by bundling your function code and the `data.json` file into a ZIP archive, and then uploading the archive to AWS Lambda.\n\nHere are the steps to follow:\n\n1. Create a directory for your Lambda function, and place your `data.json` file in the directory.\n2. Create a Node.js file for your Lambda function. Here's an example:\n```javascript\nconst fs = require('fs');\n\nexports.handler = async (event) => {\n  const data = fs.readFileSync('data.json');\n  const response = {\n    statusCode: 200,\n    body: data.toString(),\n  };\n  return response;\n};\n```\n3. Install any Node.js packages that your function depends on, and save them to the `node_modules` directory in your Lambda function directory.\n4. Create a ZIP archive of your Lambda function directory, including the `node_modules` directory.\n5. Create a new Lambda function in the AWS Management Console, and upload your ZIP archive as the function code.\n6. Test your Lambda function to make sure it can read the `data.json` file and return its contents as the response.\n\nI hope this helps you to upload your `data.json` file to AWS Lambda! Let me know if you have any further questions."
