"Arduino Uno is a popular microcontroller board that is designed to facilitate the development of electronic projects. The main function of Arduino Uno is to read inputs from sensors, switches, and other electronic components, and use this data to control outputs such as LEDs, motors, and LCD displays. The board can be programmed using the Arduino Integrated Development Environment (IDE), which is a software tool that allows users to write and upload code to the board.\n\nArduino Uno has 14 digital input/output pins, 6 of which can be used as pulse-width modulation (PWM) outputs, and 6 analog input pins [[2](https://docs.arduino.cc/hardware/uno-rev3/)]. The board is based on the Microchip ATmega328P microcontroller, and can interface with various expansion boards and shields to extend its capabilities [[3](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arduino_Uno)].\n\nArduino Uno is an open-source electronics platform that is easy to use and can be used to build a wide variety of projects, from simple circuits to complex robots. Its versatility and flexibility make it an ideal tool for hobbyists, students, and professionals who want to create interactive electronics projects [[1](https://docs.arduino.cc/learn/starting-guide/whats-arduino/)]."
"Sure, here's an example of how you can include the custom easing code in the previous script I provided:\n```\n<!-- include the GSAP library -->\n<script src=\"https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/gsap/3.6.1/gsap.min.js\"></script>\n<script>\n// create custom easing function\nCustomEase.create(\"custom\", \"0.64, 0.05, 0.35, 1\");\n\n// set variables\nlet circleParent = $(\".circle\");\nlet circleItem = \".circle_item\";\n// 360 divided by number of items\nlet rotateAmount = 360 / $(circleItem).length;\n\n// Set each item's rotation\n$(circleItem).each(function (index) {\n  let itemRotation = rotateAmount * index;\n  $(this).css(\"transform\", `rotate(${itemRotation}deg)`);\n  // Save rotation value in link's data attribute\n  $(this).find(\".circle_link\").attr(\"data-rotation\", itemRotation);\n});\n\n// reveal circle after item rotations are set\ncircleParent.css(\"opacity\", \"1.0\");\n\n// make first item active\n$(circleItem).first().addClass(\"current\");\n\n// slide parent circle to rotation of the clicked link\n$(\".circle_link\").on(\"click\", function () {\n  $(circleItem).removeClass(\"current\");\n  $(this).closest(circleItem).addClass(\"current\");\n  let rotation = $(this).attr(\"data-rotation\") * -1;\n\n  // Use TweenLite to animate the transform property with custom easing\n  TweenLite.to(circleParent, 0.5, { rotation: rotation, ease: \"custom\" });\n});\n</script>\n```\nIn this example, I've added the `CustomEase.create()` method above the rest of the script to create the custom easing function and then used it in the `TweenLite.to()` method to animate the rotation of the `circleParent` element.\nPlease make sure that you have included the GSAP library before your script and also you should have the class `.circle` in your HTML and it should be the parent element of the elements you want to rotate.\nAlso, make sure that the path for the library is correct. In this example, I've used a CDN link to include the library, but you can also download the library and use a local file path to include it in your project."
