"Once upon a time, a mother was taking her toddler daughter to the bathroom after a messy diaper blowout. The contents of the diaper had gotten all over the daughter's clothing, including her playful overalls with cartoon characters on them.\n\nThe mother quickly grabbed some wipes and cleaned the daughter up as best as she could. She then carefully removed the soiled diaper and clothes, one piece at a time. She put the dirty diaper and wipes in the toilet and went to take care of her own business.\n\nShe sat down on the toilet and did her best to relax, knowing that she had a lot of work ahead of her. She took care of her #1 and #2, and then wiped herself clean with some toilet paper. She put the used toilet paper in the toilet and flushed, watching as everything swirled around before disappearing down the drain.\n\nAfterwards, she flushed the overalls, which also went down without any issues.\n\nAfter all the dirty items were gone, the mother put a new diaper on the daughter and helped her into a fresh outfit. The daughter was excited to be wearing a new yellow sundress with white flowers and matching sandals.\n\nTogether, they finished cleaning up the bathroom and were both content after the ordeal. The mother was grateful for the extra set of clothes she had packed in the diaper bag, and the daughter was happy to be feeling fresh and clean again. She didn't even seem to miss her overalls. The mother was relieved that everything had been successfully flushed away without any problems."
"It is possible to add a `chrome.runtime` event listener in a Redux reducer, but it is not recommended. Reducers should be pure functions and should not have any side effects, such as interacting with external APIs or modifying the state outside of the current action.\n\nInstead, you should dispatch an action in response to the `chrome.runtime` event, and handle the state update in the corresponding Redux reducer. For example, you could define an action creator function that listens to the `chrome.runtime` event and dispatches an action with the updated state:\n```javascript\nfunction handleRuntimeEvent() {\n  return (dispatch, getState) => {\n    // perform some logic based on the runtime event\n    const newState = // calculate the new state based on the event\n\n    // dispatch the action with the new state\n    dispatch({ type: 'UPDATE_STATE', payload: newState });\n  }\n}\n```\nThen, you can include this action creator in your React component and dispatch it in response to the `chrome.runtime` event:\n```javascript\nimport { useDispatch } from 'react-redux';\nimport { handleRuntimeEvent } from './actions';\n\nfunction MyComponent() {\n  const dispatch = useDispatch();\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    chrome.runtime.onSomeEvent.addListener(() => {\n      dispatch(handleRuntimeEvent());\n    });\n  }, [dispatch]);\n\n  // ...\n}\n```\nIn the corresponding Redux reducer, you can handle the `UPDATE_STATE` action and update the state accordingly:\n```javascript\nfunction myReducer(state = initialState, action) {\n  switch (action.type) {\n    case 'UPDATE_STATE':\n      return { ...state, ...action.payload };\n    // ...\n  }\n}\n```"
