9)\n23. Diabetes mellitus no insulinodependiente en el embarazo (73288001)\n\nI hope this corrected list is helpful. Please let me know if you have any further questions or concerns."
"Catholics believe that Jesus intended for his followers to consume his physical body in the form of the Eucharist, not as a violation of Jewish law, but as a fulfillment of it. They believe that Jesus, as a Jew, was well-versed in the Jewish scriptures and tradition, and that he was intimately familiar with the Passover feast.\n\nDuring the Passover, the Jews would celebrate the Exodus from Egypt by sacrificing a lamb and eating its flesh. This sacrifice and consumption of the lamb was a symbol of the covenant between God and his people. Jesus, at the Last Supper, transformed this ritual into a new covenant by offering himself as the true Lamb of God, whose flesh and blood would be given for the salvation of all people.\n\nFurthermore, Catholics believe that Jesus is not merely a human being, but is also the Son of God. As such, they believe that Jesus has the power to transform bread and wine into his own body and blood. This belief is based on the words of Jesus himself when he said, \"This is my body\" and \"This cup is the new covenant in my blood\" (Luke 22:19-20). Catholics interpret these words as a literal statement of fact, rather than a metaphorical or symbolic statement.\n\nWhile it may seem to go against Jewish laws and traditions to consume human flesh and blood, Catholics believe that Jesus was offering himself as a spiritual nourishment, rather than a physical one. They do not believe that the Eucharist is cannibalistic, but rather a participation in the sacrifice of Christ, who gave his body and blood for the salvation of all humanity."
