"[The scene opens up to a classroom setting. The teacher is standing at the front of the room while the students are taking their seats.]\n\nTeacher: Good morning, everyone. Today we're going to be talking about HR systems. But before we dive into that, let's start with an icebreaker. I want everyone to say one word related to HR systems. I'll start. [The teacher says a word, and then it goes around the room until everyone has said their word.]\n\nTeacher: Great! Let's write the words on the board around the phrase \"HR systems\". [The teacher writes \"HR systems\" on the board and then writes the words around it as the students dictate them.]\n\nTeacher: So, what are HR systems? They're software applications designed to streamline and automate HR-related tasks and processes within an organization. Their role in business is to help organizations manage their workforce more efficiently and effectively.\n\n[The teacher continues on to talk about the impact of HR systems on employee management and productivity for 10 minutes, and then talks about the importance of HR systems in maintaining legal compliance for another 10 minutes.]\n\nTeacher: Now, let's move on to the different types of HR systems. There are payroll systems, performance management systems, applicant tracking systems, HR information systems, talent management systems, time and attendance systems. Each system has its own benefits and challenges. I want you to get into pairs and discuss the benefits and challenges associated with each HR system mentioned above.\n\n[The students discuss the different types of HR systems and their benefits and challenges in pairs for 10 minutes, then some pairs are called on to present to the class.]\n\nTeacher: Now, let's move on to the group presentations. I want you to collaborate with your group to create a new HR system for a fictional company. Remember, collaboration and teamwork are important in the workplace. After you've created your HR system, you'll evaluate the stakeholders and their impact assessment of the proposed HR system.\n\n[The teacher continues on to give instructions for the group presentations, and then the students have a group discussion for 10 minutes.]\n\nTeacher: Okay, now it's time for the group presentations. We'll start with Group A, and then move on to the other groups.\n\n[The groups present their HR systems and evaluations for 25 minutes, and then the teacher summarizes the week's lesson for 5 minutes.]\n\nTeacher: That's all for today. Great work, everyone!"
