"To order the result set by `TotalRequestedAmount`, you can use the column alias in the `ORDER BY` clause, like this:\n```SQL\nSELECT s.\"Id\", s.\"UserId\", SUM(s.\"RequestedAmount\") as TotalRequestedAmount, s.\"Status\"\nFROM \"Swaps\" s\nWHERE s.\"SourceCurrencyId\" = 27 AND s.\"Status\" = 1\nGROUP BY s.\"Id\", s.\"UserId\", s.\"CreatedDate\", s.\"Status\"\nORDER BY TotalRequestedAmount;\n```\nIn this updated query, we've used the `TotalRequestedAmount` column alias in the `ORDER BY` clause, so the result set will be sorted by the sum of requested amounts for each swap.\n\nNote that the column alias can be used in the `ORDER BY` clause because it is derived from an aggregate function in the `SELECT` clause. If you try to use the `SUM()` function directly in the `ORDER BY` clause, it won't work because `SUM()` is an aggregate function that doesn't operate on individual rows."
"Certainly! Here are some more examples of viruses and their intermediate hosts:\n\n1. Hendra virus (1994): Fruit bats (Pteropus species) were identified as the natural reservoir host for Hendra virus, which can cause severe respiratory and neurological disease in horses and humans. The virus was first identified in Hendra, a suburb of Brisbane, Australia, in 1994, where it caused a fatal outbreak in horses and their trainers. Since then, there have been sporadic outbreaks in horses in Australia, with occasional spillover to humans. The virus has also been found in other bat species.\n2. Nipah virus (1998): Fruit bats (Pteropus species) were also identified as the natural reservoir host for Nipah virus, which can cause severe respiratory and neurological disease in humans and animals. The virus was first identified during an outbreak in Malaysia in 1998, where it caused an epidemic of encephalitis in pigs and humans. The virus has since been identified in bats and other animals in Asia.\n3. Ebola virus (1976): Fruit bats (mainly species of the genus Rousettus) are believed to be the natural reservoir host for Ebola virus, which can cause severe hemorrhagic fever in humans and other primates. The virus was first identified during simultaneous outbreaks in Sudan and the Democratic Republic of Congo in 1976. While the exact role of fruit bats in transmitting the virus to humans is not fully understood, they are believed to play a key role in the virus's ecology.\n4. Marburg virus (1967): Fruit bats (species of the genus Rousettus) are also believed to be the natural reservoir host for Marburg virus, which can cause severe hemorrhagic fever in humans and other primates. The virus was first identified during an outbreak in Marburg, Germany, in 1967, where it caused a cluster of severe cases in laboratory workers who had been exposed to African green monkeys imported from Uganda. Since then, sporadic outbreaks of Marburg virus have occurred in Africa, with occasional spillover to humans.\n5. Hantavirus (1993): Several species of rodents have been identified as the natural reservoir host for hantavirus, which can cause hantavirus pulmonary syndrome (HPS) in humans. The virus was first identified in the southwestern United States in 1993, during an outbreak of HPS among Native Americans. The deer mouse (Peromyscus maniculatus) was identified as the primary rodent host for the virus in that region, although other rodent species can also carry the virus.\n\nIn general, the number of animals found infected with the virus can vary widely depending on the virus and the host species. In some cases, only a small number of animals may be found to be carrying the virus, while in other cases the virus may be more widespread in the host population."
"Cesar Chavez, the American labor leader and civil rights activist, was known for his lifelong work advocating for the rights of farmworkers, particularly those of Mexican and Filipino descent. He co-founded the United Farm Workers (UFW) union and led several successful strikes and boycotts in the 1960s and 1970s to improve the working conditions and wages of farmworkers.\n\nWhile Chavez himself was not a cook or a chef, he was known for his advocacy for healthy and sustainable food systems. He believed that everyone, regardless of their socio-economic status, deserved access to fresh, nutritious food. As part of his work with the UFW, he promoted the idea of \"La Causa\" (the cause), which included fighting for fair wages and working conditions for farmworkers, as well as promoting organic and sustainable farming practices.\n\nChavez and the UFW also advocated for consumers to support their cause by boycotting non-union grapes and lettuce, which became a powerful symbol of the labor movement. Through his work, Chavez helped bring attention to the struggles of farmworkers and to the importance of fair labor practices in the food industry."
