"Here's an example of an HTML search form that can be used to submit a search query to a Laravel controller, which then retrieves the search results and displays them on another HTML page:\n```\n<!-- Search form -->\n<form action=\"/search\" method=\"POST\">\n    @csrf\n    <input type=\"text\" name=\"query\" placeholder=\"Search...\">\n    <button type=\"submit\">Search</button>\n</form>\n```\nIn this example, the form is using the `POST` method to submit the search query to the `/search` route. The `@csrf` directive is used to include a CSRF token in the form, which is required for security in Laravel.\nThe input has a name attribute, so that the data can be accessed in the controller.\n\nYou also need to set up a route to handle the form submission in `web.php` file in the route directory\n```\nRoute::post('/search', 'SearchController@search');\n```\nThen you can create a method in SearchController to handle the post data and do the search logic\n```\nclass SearchController extends Controller {\n\n    public function search(Request $request) {\n        $query = $request->input('query');\n\n        // do the search logic and get the results\n\n        return view('search-results', ['results' => $results]);\n    }\n}\n```\nYou can create a view file `search-results.blade.php` in the views folder to display the search results\n```\n<!-- Search Results -->\n<div class=\"search-results\">\n    <h2>Search Results</h2>\n    <ul>\n    @foreach($results as $result)\n        <li>{{ $result->title }}</li>\n    @endforeach\n    </ul>\n</div>\n```\nIn this example, the search controller receives the query, performs the search logic and retrieves the search results. Then it passes the results to the view `search-results` and renders it. The view then displays the results on the page.\nPlease keep in mind that this is just a basic example, and you should adjust it to suit the specific requirements of your application.\nYou can also use Laravel's built-in validation and error handling to ensure that the data is valid before processing it.\nYou can also use pagination to handle a large amount of results and make the search more efficient"
"Yes, you can use multiple validators for one field in Pydantic. Here's an example:\n```python\nfrom pydantic import BaseModel, validator\n\nclass User(BaseModel):\n    username: str\n    \n    @validator('username')\n    def username_min_length(cls, v):\n        if len(v) < 4:\n            raise ValueError('Username must be at least 4 characters long')\n        return v\n    \n    @validator('username')\n    def username_max_length(cls, v):\n        if len(v) > 32:\n            raise ValueError('Username must be at most 32 characters long')\n        return v\n```\nIn this example, the `username` field has two validators: `username_min_length` and `username_max_length`. Both validators receive the value of the `username` field as the first argument (`v`). If a validator raises a `ValueError`, it means that the validation failed, and Pydantic will raise a `ValidationError` with the error message.\n\nYou can add as many validators as you want for a field by adding more `@validator` decorators to the field."
