"Sure, here's an example Python code for plotting the new growth rate function:\n```python\nimport numpy as np\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\n# Define functions for light, water, nutrient, and temperature\ndef light(t):\n    return 1 + 0.5 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * t / 365)\n\ndef water(t):\n    return 0.5 + 0.5 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * t / 365)\n\ndef nutrient(t):\n    return 0.8 + 0.2 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * t / 365)\n\ndef temp(t):\n    return 20 + 10 * np.sin(2 * np.pi * t / 365)\n\n# Define parameters for logistic function\nk = 1.0\na = 0.01\nb = 0.5\n\n# Define function for intrinsic growth rate\ndef growth_rate(t):\n    return k * light(t) * water(t) * nutrient(t) * temp(t) / (1 + np.exp(-a * (light(t) + water(t) + nutrient(t) + temp(t)) + b))\n\n# Plot growth rate as a function of time\nt = np.linspace(0, 365, 1000)\ng = growth_rate(t)\n\nfig, ax = plt.subplots()\nax.plot(t, g)\nax.set_xlabel('Time (days)')\nax.set_ylabel('Intrinsic growth rate')\nax.set_title('Intrinsic growth rate as a function of time')\n\nplt.show()\n```\nThis code defines the four environmental factor functions (light, water, nutrient, and temperature) as sinusoidal functions of time, and the logistic function for intrinsic growth rate as a function of these environmental factors. The resulting growth rate function is then plotted as a function of time using Matplotlib.\n\nYou can modify the environmental factor functions and logistic function parameters as needed for your specific context."
