"Sure! Here's the full math for the calculation of P(sum <= 4):\n\nP(sum <= 4) = (1-p)^5 + 5p(1-p)^4 + 10p^2(1-p)^3 + 10p^3(1-p)^2 + 5p^4(1-p)^1\n\nStarting from the first term, (1-p)^5, this represents the probability of all 5 bits being 0. The number 5 in the exponent represents the number of trials, and (1-p) represents the probability of failure in each trial, i.e., the probability of getting a 0.\n\nThe second term, 5p(1-p)^4, represents the probability of getting exactly 1 1 and 4 0's. The number 5 in front of p is the number of ways to choose 1 success (getting a 1) out of 5 trials. The (1-p)^4 in the exponent represents the probability of getting 4 failures (getting 0's).\n\nThe third term, 10p^2(1-p)^3, represents the probability of getting exactly 2 1's and 3 0's. The number 10 in front of p^2 is the number of ways to choose 2 success out of 5 trials. The (1-p)^3 in the exponent represents the probability of getting 3 failures.\n\nThe fourth term, 10p^3(1-p)^2, represents the probability of getting exactly 3 1's and 2 0's. The number 10 in front of p^3 is the number of ways to choose 3 success out of 5 trials. The (1-p)^2 in the exponent represents the probability of getting 2 failures.\n\nThe fifth term, 5p^4(1-p)^1, represents the probability of getting exactly 4 1's and 1 0. The number 5 in front of p^4 is the number of ways to choose 4 success out of 5 trials. The (1-p)^1 in the exponent represents the probability of getting 1 failure.\n\nAdding these terms gives us the final expression:\n\nP(sum <= 4) = (1-p)^5 + 5p(1-p)^4 + 10p^2(1-p)^3 + 10p^3(1-p)^2 + 5p^4(1-p)^1 = 1 - p^5"
