"One aspect of the Eucharist where the theology evolved in the first two hundred years of Christianity was the understanding of the real presence of Christ in the Eucharist. While the belief in the real presence of Christ in the Eucharist was present from the earliest days of Christianity, the precise understanding of how Christ was present evolved over time.\n\nFor example, in the early 2nd century, Ignatius of Antioch wrote in his letter to the Smyrnaeans that the Docetists denied the reality of Christ's body and blood in the Eucharist. He wrote, \"They abstain from the Eucharist and from prayer, because they do not confess that the Eucharist is the flesh of our Savior Jesus Christ, which suffered for our sins and which the Father, in His goodness, raised up again\" (Chapter 7).\n\nLater, in the mid-2nd century, Justin Martyr in his First Apology described the Eucharist as the \"flesh and blood of the same Jesus who became incarnate\" (Chapter 66). However, he did not provide a detailed explanation of how this was possible.\n\nBy the end of the 2nd century, the Church Fathers began to use the term \"transubstantiation\" to describe the change that occurred in the Eucharist. For example, Irenaeus of Lyons wrote in his Against Heresies, \"He has declared the cup, a part of creation, to be his own blood, from which he causes our blood to flow; and the bread, a part of creation, he has established as his own body, from which he gives increase unto our bodies\" (Book 5, Chapter 2).\n\nThus, while the belief in the real presence of Christ in the Eucharist was present from the earliest days of Christianity, the precise understanding of how Christ was present evolved over time."
"`@future` methods can be executed by using the `System.start()` method. For example, the following code demonstrates how to execute a `@future` method:\n```typescript\npublic class MyFutureMethod {\n    @future\n    public static void myMethod(String name) {\n        // Perform some operation\n    }\n}\n\n// To execute the @future method\nMyFutureMethod.myMethod('John Doe');\n```\n`Queueable` jobs can be executed by using the `System.enqueueJob()` method. For example, the following code demonstrates how to execute a `Queueable` job:\n```java\npublic class MyQueueableJob implements Queueable {\n    public void execute(QueueableContext context) {\n        // Perform some operation\n    }\n}\n\n// To execute the Queueable job\nID jobID = System.enqueueJob(new MyQueueableJob());\n```\n`Batchable` jobs can be executed by using the `Database.executeBatch()` method. For example, the following code demonstrates how to execute a `Batchable` job:\n```typescript\npublic class MyBatchableJob implements Database.Batchable<sObject>, Database.AllowsCallouts {\n    public Database.QueryLocator start(Database.BatchableContext context) {\n        // Returns the query locator for the records to be processed\n        return Database.getQueryLocator([SELECT Id FROM Account]);\n    }\n\n    public void execute(Database.BatchableContext context, List<sObject> records) {\n        // Perform some operation\n    }\n\n    public void finish(Database.BatchableContext context) {\n        // Perform some operation\n    }\n}\n\n// To execute the Batchable job\nID batchJobID = Database.executeBatch(new MyBatchableJob(), 200);\n```\nNote that the second argument in the `Database.executeBatch()` method is the batch size, which determines the number of records that are processed in each batch."
"As Frodo and Sam stood atop Mount Doom, gazing out at the destruction wrought by the Ring's destruction, Frodo turned to Sam with tears in his eyes.\n\n\"Sam,\" he said, his voice trembling. \"I couldn't have done it without you.\"\n\nSam looked at him, his own eyes brimming with tears. \"You don't have to thank me, Mr. Frodo,\" he said. \"I couldn't have done it without you either.\"\n\nThe two friends embraced, holding each other tightly as they wept. They had been through so much together, from the peaceful days of the Shire to the dark depths of Mordor, and the bond that had formed between them was stronger than any other.\n\nFrodo remembered the day when Sam had first been assigned to be his gardener, and how Sam had become so much more than that. Sam had been his confidante, his companion, and his protector. Without Sam's unwavering loyalty and strength, Frodo knew he would never have made it to this moment.\n\nBut Sam had also been his friend, the person who had shared in the joys and sorrows of the journey, the one who had made him laugh when all seemed lost. Frodo knew that Sam's unwavering courage and love had been the true source of their success.\n\nAs they made their way back to the Shire, Frodo and Sam talked about their adventures, reliving the moments that had brought them together and made them stronger. They reminisced about the time they spent in the Elven realm of Lothlorien, where they had felt peace and wonder amidst the dangers of their quest. They laughed about the time they had been captured by the Orcs and Sam had tricked them into thinking they were on their side. And they spoke of the pain they had endured, the loss of their friends Boromir and Gandalf, and the scars that would always remain.\n\nBut above all, they spoke of their love for each other, a bond that had grown stronger with every challenge they had faced. They knew that they would always be there for each other, no matter what challenges lay ahead, and that their friendship would endure long after they had left Middle-earth.\n\nYears later, when Frodo was old and grey and preparing to leave Middle-earth for the Undying Lands, Sam was by his side. \"I'll never forget you, Mr. Frodo,\" he said, his voice choked with emotion. \"You're the best friend I ever had.\"\n\n\"And you're the best friend I ever had, Sam,\" Frodo replied, smiling weakly. \"I couldn't have asked for a better companion on this journey.\"\n\nAs Frodo sailed off into the sunset, Sam watched him go, tears streaming down his face. But he knew that Frodo was finally at peace, and that their bond would never be broken, even across the seas.\n\nAnd so, in the end, the relationship between Frodo and Sam endured, a testament to the power of friendship and loyalty in the face of even the greatest challenges. Theirs was a love that had sustained them through the darkest of days and had given them hope for a brighter tomorrow, a love that would always be a part of them, wherever their journeys took them."
"Web search results:\n\n[1] \"The 1D Infinite Well. An electron is trapped in a one-dimensional infinite potential well of length \\(4.0 \\times 10^{-10}\\, m\\). Find the three longest wavelength photons emitted by the electron as it changes energy levels in the well. The allowed energy states of a particle of mass m trapped in an infinite potential well of length L are\"\nURL: https://phys.libretexts.org/Bookshelves/Modern\\_Physics/Book%3A\\_Spiral\\_Modern\\_Physics\\_(D'Alessandris)/6%3A\\_The\\_Schrodinger\\_Equation/6.2%3A\\_Solving\\_the\\_1D\\_Infinite\\_Square\\_Well\n\n[2] \"You can easily show this by calculating the potential energy of a test charge when you bring the test charge from the reference point at infinity to point P: V P = V 1 + V 2 + \u22ef + V N = \u2211 1 N V i. Note that electric potential follows the same principle of superposition as electric field and electric potential energy.\"\nURL: https://openstax.org/books/university-physics-volume-2/pages/7-3-calculations-of-electric-potential\n\n[3] \"I'll again repeat the usual saying that the absolute value of potential energy doesn't matter. What matters is the relative difference. Having said that we can define the potential energy of a charge at some point relative to some other point. You can think of potential energy as the energy of a system, and not that of a single charge.\"\nURL: https://physics.stackexchange.com/questions/494612/what-is-the-work-done-in-bringing-a-charge-from-infinity-to-the-location-of-anot\nCurrent date: 3/28/2023\n\nInstructions: Using the provided web search results, write a comprehensive reply to the given query. Make sure to cite results using [[number](URL)] notation after the reference. If the provided search results refer to multiple subjects with the same name, write separate answers for each subject.\nQuery: Rewrite the above plan assuming an infinite amount of energy and revised economic paradigmsShare Prompt"
