"Yes, that's correct. The performance difference between searching for a base64-encoded string value and an integer value, when used as an indexed field, should be minimal. The key factor in indexing performance is the structure and organization of the index, not the data type or size of the indexed field.\n\nWhen you create an index on a field, the database organizes the data in a way that allows for faster lookups. This is true for both string and integer fields. While it's true that base64-encoded strings can be longer than simple integers, the difference in performance is likely to be negligible for most practical use cases.\n\nThe main consideration in choosing an indexed field should be the query patterns of your application. If you frequently search for documents based on a specific field, indexing that field will likely improve query performance, regardless of whether the field contains base64-encoded strings or integers.\n\nHowever, always remember that indexing comes with trade-offs, such as increased storage space and potential slowdowns in write operations. Be sure to carefully consider these factors when deciding which fields to index."
"Logicism is a philosophical and mathematical doctrine that holds that mathematics can be reduced to or derived from logic. The idea is that mathematical concepts and theorems can be defined in terms of logical concepts and logical reasoning, and that mathematical proofs can be reduced to logical proofs.\n\nThe origins of logicism can be traced back to the work of Gottlob Frege and Bertrand Russell in the late 19th and early 20th centuries. They proposed that mathematical concepts such as numbers, sets, and functions can be defined in terms of logical concepts such as classes, relations, and propositional functions. They also proposed that mathematical proofs can be reduced to logical proofs, and that mathematical theorems can be derived from logical axioms and rules of inference.\n\nThe most famous and influential example of Logicism is the program of Frege and Russell to reduce the whole of mathematics to logic, and specifically, to the theory of sets, and later on to the theory of types and the theory of classes.\n\nLogicism faced challenges from other philosophers and mathematicians, such as David Hilbert and Kurt G\u00f6del, who argued that mathematics cannot be reduced to logic alone, and that there are mathematical concepts and proofs that cannot be reduced to logical concepts and proofs.\n\nIn summary, Logicism is a philosophical and mathematical doctrine that holds that mathematics can be reduced to or derived from logic. It proposes that mathematical concepts and theorems can be defined in terms of logical concepts and logical reasoning, and that mathematical proofs can be reduced to logical proofs. It was proposed by Gottlob Frege and Bertrand Russell in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, but faced challenges from other philosophers and mathematicians who argued that mathematics cannot be reduced to logic alone."
