"Here is a code sample for adding a delete method for removing one or multiple records, as well as a delete field method in PHP:\n```php\nclass Entity {\n  private $tableName;\n  private $fields = array();\n  private $records = array();\n\n  public function __construct($tableName) {\n    $this->tableName = $tableName;\n  }\n\n  public function __get($fieldName) {\n    if (array_key_exists($fieldName, $this->fields)) {\n      return $this->fields[$fieldName];\n    }\n  }\n\n  public function __set($fieldName, $fieldValue) {\n    $this->fields[$fieldName] = $fieldValue;\n    // Add the field to all existing records\n    foreach ($this->records as &$record) {\n      $record[$fieldName] = $fieldValue;\n    }\n  }\n\n  public function addRecord(array $record) {\n    $this->records[] = $record;\n  }\n\n  public function deleteRecord($recordIndex) {\n    unset($this->records[$recordIndex]);\n  }\n\n  public function deleteRecords(array $recordIndices) {\n    foreach ($recordIndices as $index) {\n      unset($this->records[$index]);\n    }\n  }\n\n  public function deleteField($fieldName) {\n    unset($this->fields[$fieldName]);\n    // Remove the field from all records\n    foreach ($this->records as &$record) {\n      unset($record[$fieldName]);\n    }\n  }\n\n  public function save() {\n    // Save the table to disk\n  }\n\n  public function load() {\n    // Load the table from disk\n  }\n}\n```\nNote: This is a very basic implementation and you may need to modify it to fit your specific requirements. The `save` and `load` methods are left blank as they depend on your specific file format and storage mechanism."
