"I apologize for the mistake in my previous response. In my previous response, I provided a SPICE code for an RC filter with a resistor of 1 kilohm and a capacitor of 10 microfarads, which would result in a -3dB bandwidth of around 159 Hz, not 3 kHz as requested.\n\nTo build an RC filter with a 3kHz bandwidth in SPICE and plot the frequency response from 1Hz to 100kHz, you can use the following SPICE code:\n```\n* RC filter circuit with a 3kHz bandwidth\nV1 1 0 10   ; 10V source\nR1 1 2 3k   ; 3 kilohm resistor\nC1 2 0 1u   ; 1 microfarad capacitor\n\n* Connect negative end of voltage source to ground\nGND 0 0\n\n* Perform AC analysis of RC filter circuit\n.AC DEC 1 100k\n.PLOT AC V(2)\n.END\n```\nThis SPICE code defines a voltage source (V1) with a voltage of 10V, a resistor (R1) with a resistance of 3 kilohms, and a capacitor (C1) with a capacitance of 1 microfarad. The voltage source is connected between nodes 1 and 0, and the resistor (R1) is connected between nodes 1 and 2. The capacitor (C1) is connected between nodes 2 and 0. Node 0 represents the ground node in this circuit.\n\nTo plot the frequency response of this circuit, the `AC` analysis is used with a frequency sweep from 1 Hz to 100 kHz in decade increments (logarithmic scale). The `.PLOT` command will plot the voltage at node 2 (V(2)) at each frequency point. The `.END` command indicates the end of the analysis.\n\nThe -3dB bandwidth of the RC filter can be determined by looking for the frequency at which the voltage at node 2 is 3 dB below the maximum value. The -3dB bandwidth is the range of frequencies where the voltage at node 2 is within 3 dB of the maximum value. In this case, the -3dB bandwidth of the RC filter should be around 3 kHz.\n\nI apologize for the mistake in my previous response and hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions or need further assistance."
