"Sure! Here's the modified script that searches for all `.c` files in a directory and its subdirectories:\n```python\nimport os\nimport re\n\n# specify the directory to search for C files\ndir_path = \"path/to/your/directory\"\n\n# specify the names of the functions you want to search for\nfunction_names = [\"M0LOG\", \"M0LOG64\"]\n\n# use a regular expression to find all lines that contain the specified function names\npattern = r\"\\b(\" + \"|\".join(function_names) + r\")\\b\\s*\\(\\s*[^,]*\\s*,\\s*\\\"([^\\\"\\n]*)\\\"\"\n\n# iterate over all files in the directory and its subdirectories\nfor root, dirs, files in os.walk(dir_path):\n    for file in files:\n        if file.endswith(\".c\"):\n            # open the C file and read its contents\n            file_path = os.path.join(root, file)\n            with open(file_path, \"r\") as f:\n                file_contents = f.read()\n            # find all lines that contain the specified function names\n            matching_lines = [line for line in file_contents.split(\"\\n\") if re.search(pattern, line)]\n            # extract the second parameter from each matching line\n            extracted_params = [re.search(pattern, line).group(2) for line in matching_lines]\n            # write the extracted parameters to a lookup table in C format (K&R style)\n            lookup_table = \"char *lookup_table[] = {\\n\"\n            for param in extracted_params:\n                lookup_table += \"\\t\\\"\" + param.replace('\\\\', '\\\\\\\\').replace('\"', r'\\\"').strip() + \"\\\",\\n\"\n            lookup_table += \"};\\n\"\n            # write the lookup table to a file with the same name as the C file\n            lookup_table_file_path = os.path.splitext(file_path)[0] + \".lookup.c\"\n            with open(lookup_table_file_path, \"w\") as f:\n                f.write(lookup_table)\n```\nIn this version of the script, the `os.walk()` function is used to recursively traverse the directory tree and find all `.c` files. For each `.c` file, the script opens the file, reads its contents, searches for the specified function names using a regular expression, extracts the second parameter from each matching line, and writes the extracted parameters to a lookup table in a new file with the same name as the `.c` file, but with the suffix `.lookup.c`. The resulting lookup tables will be formatted in K&R style."
