"Entering adulthood is a momentous time for anyone, as the urge to explore the world and assert our independence is a compelling force for many. However, the factors that influence this experience can differ significantly. For instance, someone starting a job may have different needs and priorities than an individual planning to pursue university studies. Overall, I believe that young adults, especially those attending university or similar pursuits, should continue to live with their families for an extended period.\n\nFirstly, financial considerations are essential in this decision. Although some young adults can become self-sufficient relatively quickly, the costs of renting a house, university tuition, purchasing a car, or buying insurance are high in most parts of the world. As a university student, I recall struggling to pay bills and cover living expenses when attempting to live independently, which negatively impacted my academic performance.\n\nAdditionally, living with family can significantly enhance a young adult's academic performance. With familial support, it is easier to concentrate on studies. Although some families may be distracting or stressful, for most individuals, living at home provides a conducive environment for better meals, a peaceful place to study, and a good night's sleep. For instance, a friend from my university days lived in a shared house with other students. While life was a constant party for him, he did not eat or study well, which inevitably led to poor grades. He had to retake several subjects, and he finished his degree later than many of his peers.\n\nFinally, living with parents does not mean that young adults cannot develop independence. Although some parents may find it challenging to accept that their children have grown up, it is possible to strike a balance that respects the young adult's adulthood while still providing appropriate support. During my university days, I lived with my parents, and they respected me as an adult, as well as their child, without interfering too much or limiting my independence. I believe many young adults can enjoy similar experiences, making it unfair to assume that living with family impedes their independence. In reality, the secure environment of the family can be a good place to navigate the transition to adulthood for both the young adult and the parents.\n\nIn conclusion, based on the points explored above, I believe that, in most cases, young adults benefit from continuing to live with their families for an extended period. Families are precious and play an essential role in the fabric of nurturing societies, serving as powerful guides for children as they navigate the path to independence."
"MK points out Wukong to Macaque, who narrows his eyes and tenses his muscles.\n\nMacaque: \"He's just sitting there watching us. That can't be good.\"\n\nMK: \"What do we do?\"\n\nMacaque: \"We keep moving. We don't want to stay in one place for too long with him around.\"\n\nMK nods, still feeling the fear from their earlier encounter with Wukong. They continue on their clouds, but Macaque keeps a close eye on Wukong, who seems to be following them at a distance.\n\nMK: \"Why is he just watching us like that?\"\n\nMacaque: \"Who knows what's going on in that monkey's head. We just need to keep moving and stay alert.\"\n\nMK nods again, trying to stay calm. They fly for what feels like hours, but every time MK looks back, Wukong is still there, watching. Finally, Macaque breaks the silence.\n\nMacaque: \"We need to lose him. I have an idea.\"\n\nHe whispers the plan to MK, who nods in agreement. They change course, flying towards a thick cluster of clouds. As they near the clouds, Macaque jumps from his cloud and disappears into the mist. MK can hear Wukong's laughter echoing in the distance as he disappears into the cloud. After what feels like an eternity, Macaque returns.\n\nMacaque: \"I lost him. He didn't follow us into the clouds.\"\n\nMK breathes a sigh of relief.\n\nMK: \"Thank you. I don't know what I would have done if he caught up to us again.\"\n\nMacaque nods.\n\nMacaque: \"We just have to stay one step ahead of him. We'll make it through this.\""
"In the `.storybook/main.js` file, the `framework` field specifies the framework that you are using for your project.\n\nThe `framework` field is used to tell Storybook which framework specific configurations to use. For example, if you are using React for your project, you would specify the `react` framework in your `.storybook/main.js` file.\n\nHere is an example of how to specify the `react` framework in your `.storybook/main.js` file:\n```\nmodule.exports = {\n  framework: \"react\"\n};\n```\nYou can also specify multiple frameworks in your `.storybook/main.js` file. For example:\n```\nmodule.exports = {\n  framework: [\"react\", \"vue\"]\n};\n```\nIn this example, Storybook will use the React and Vue specific configurations.\n\nI hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions."
