"In Terraria, you can check the in-game time by doing the following:\n\n1. The Clock: The clock is an item that can be purchased from the merchant NPC. It displays the current in-game time when used.\n2. The in-game clock: The in-game clock is a feature that is always present on the screen, it displays the current in-game time, it's located in the top-right corner of the screen.\n3. Using the map: The map that can be accessed by pressing the \"M\" key on the keyboard, will also display the current in-game time at the top of the map screen.\n4. Using a Timer: Timers are items that can be crafted using wires and a clock, they will also display the current in-game time on the screen.\n\nYou can use any of the above methods to check the in-game time, it's just a matter of preference. Knowing the in-game time can be useful to plan your activities, like when to go mining, hunting, farming and also to know when it's going to be day or night."
"Got it, thanks for the clarification. Here's an updated code example that extracts the \"headline\" of each text block based on the font size and style:\n```python\nimport fitz\nimport re\n\n# Open the PDF file\nwith fitz.open('example.pdf') as doc:\n\n    # Loop through all the pages\n    for page in doc:\n\n        # Extract the text and layout information\n        blocks = page.getText('dict')['blocks']\n\n        # Process each block to extract text\n        for block in blocks:\n\n            # Ignore non-text blocks\n            if block['type'] != 0:\n                continue\n\n            # Extract the text and its layout information\n            block_text = \"\"\n            block_headline = \"\"\n            for line in block['lines']:\n                for span in line['spans']:\n                    if span['size'] > 14 and 'bold' in span['font'].lower():\n                        block_headline += span['text'] + \" \"\n                    else:\n                        block_text += span['text']\n\n            bbox = block['bbox']\n\n            # Perform layout-based postprocessing\n            if bbox[3] - bbox[1] > 50:\n                block_headline = re.sub('\\n+', '\\n', block_headline)\n                block_headline = re.sub('[ ]+', ' ', block_headline)\n                block_text = re.sub('\\n+', '\\n', block_text)\n                block_text = re.sub('[ ]+', ' ', block_text)\n                print(f\"{block_headline.strip()}\\n{block_text}\")\n```\nIn this updated code, we check the font size and style of each span to identify the \"headline\" of the block. Specifically, we look for spans with a font size greater than 14 and with the word \"bold\" in the font name (e.g., \"Times-Bold\"). We concatenate these spans together to form the \"headline\" for the block. We then concatenate all the remaining spans to form the main text. We perform layout-based postprocessing on both the headline and the text, and print them together.\n\nNote that the font size and style thresholds may need to be adjusted for different PDFs depending on the layout and formatting."
"After advanced calculus, a student might be prepared to study the following subjects, depending on their interests and career goals:\n\n1. Linear Algebra: This is the study of systems of linear equations, and the properties of matrices and vectors.\n2. Differential Equations: This is the study of equations that describe the rates of change of functions and their relationships to the underlying physical processes they represent.\n3. Abstract Algebra: This is the study of algebraic structures such as groups, rings, and fields, and their properties and applications.\n4. Real Analysis: This is the study of the real number system, and the properties of functions and sequences defined on the real numbers.\n5. Complex Analysis: This is the study of complex functions and their properties, and the study of functions and integrals in the complex plane.\n6. Numerical Analysis: This is the study of numerical methods for solving mathematical problems, and the design and analysis of algorithms for scientific and engineering applications.\n7. Applied Mathematics: This encompasses a wide range of fields in which mathematical models are used to study and solve real-world problems, including physics, engineering, economics, and finance.\n\nThis list is by no means exhaustive, and the next steps for a student after advanced calculus will depend on their interests, abilities, and career goals."
