"There are several tools that an application can use to pull client data from Salesforce and push data back into their Salesforce accounts. Some of these tools include:\n\n1. Salesforce APIs: Salesforce provides a number of APIs that allow developers to access and manipulate data within Salesforce. These APIs include the REST API, SOAP API, and Bulk API.\n2. Salesforce DX: Salesforce DX is a set of tools and processes that allow developers to build, test, and deploy applications on the Salesforce platform. It includes a command-line interface (CLI) that allows developers to retrieve data from Salesforce and push data back into their Salesforce accounts.\n3. Salesforce Connect: Salesforce Connect is a set of tools that allow developers to connect external data sources to Salesforce. It includes a number of adapters that allow developers to connect to various types of data sources, such as databases and web services.\n4. Salesforce Lightning Connect: Salesforce Lightning Connect is a tool that allows developers to connect external data sources to Salesforce in real-time. It uses OData (Open Data Protocol) to connect to external data sources and retrieve data on-demand.\n5. Salesforce AppExchange: The Salesforce AppExchange is a marketplace for third-party apps and integrations that can be used to access and manipulate data within Salesforce. It includes a wide variety of tools and integrations that can be used to pull client data from Salesforce and push data back into their Salesforce accounts.\n\nIn summary, there are several tools that an application can use to pull client data from Salesforce and push data back into their Salesforce accounts. These tools include Salesforce APIs, Salesforce DX, Salesforce Connect, Salesforce Lightning Connect, and the Salesforce AppExchange."
"There are a few things that could be causing the issue where clicking on the extension icon does not open the expected page. Here are some troubleshooting steps you can try:\n\n1. Make sure that your `manifest.json` file is in the root directory of your extension folder, and that it is properly formatted with the correct properties and values.\n2. Check that your `index.html` and `script.js` files are in the correct directory and that they are properly linked to each other. Make sure that the `script.js` file is included in the `index.html` file using a script tag.\n3. Ensure that your extension is enabled by going to the Chrome extensions page (chrome://extensions/) and making sure that the toggle switch for your extension is turned on.\n4. Check the browser console for any error messages that might indicate why the expected page is not opening. You can open the console by right-clicking anywhere on the page, selecting \"Inspect\", and then selecting the \"Console\" tab.\n5. Check that your API key and endpoint are correct and that your extension has permission to access the API. You can check this by looking at the permissions in your `manifest.json` file.\n6. Try loading your extension in a new Chrome profile or incognito mode to see if any other extensions or settings are interfering with it.\n7. Try restarting Chrome or your computer, as this can sometimes resolve issues with extensions.\n\nHopefully one of these troubleshooting steps will help you identify the issue and get your extension working as expected."
